\description{
\code{brulee_tab_icl()} prepares the pretrained TabICL (Tabular In-Context
Learning) foundation model from Qu \emph{et al} (2025) for prediction. TabICL is a
transformer that makes predictions on tabular data by \emph{in-context learning}:
it is not trained on your data. Instead, the released pretrained weights are
loaded and the model conditions on your training rows at prediction time,
much like a few-shot language model conditions on its prompt. Both
classification and regression are supported.
}
\details{
\subsection{In-context learning}{

Unlike the other \pkg{brulee} models, \code{brulee_tab_icl()} does not train any
parameters. The pretrained network is fixed; "fitting" simply validates and
stores the (encoded) training predictors and outcomes together with a
reference to the checkpoint. At \code{\link[=predict]{predict()}} time the model is given the
training rows as labelled context alongside the new rows and produces
predictions in a single forward pass. Because the training data are stored on
the fitted object, larger training sets make the object larger and prediction
slower.
}

\subsection{Architecture}{

TabICL processes a table through three transformer stages:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Column embedding}: a per-column set transformer turns each cell into a
distribution-aware embedding, optionally informed by the target.
\item \strong{Row interaction}: a transformer with rotary position encoding mixes the
feature embeddings within each row and aggregates them with learnable CLS
tokens.
\item \strong{In-context learning}: a dataset-level transformer lets the test rows
attend to the labelled training rows to produce class logits
(classification) or quantiles (regression).
}
}

\subsection{Preprocessing}{

Predictors are made numeric (factors and characters are ordinal-encoded;
numeric columns are mean-imputed). For each ensemble member the predictors are
then standardized, optionally transformed (\code{norm_methods}), and have outliers
clipped, mirroring the reference implementation. Factor outcomes are label
encoded; numeric outcomes are standardized internally and predictions are
returned on the original scale. There is \emph{no need to pre-encode factors as
indicators}.
}

\subsection{Ensembling}{

With \code{n_estimators > 1}, several views of the data are created by permuting
features and (for classification) shuffling class labels, each optionally with
a different normalization. Class logits are averaged across members and
converted to probabilities with a temperature softmax; regression means are
averaged. \code{n_estimators = 1} uses a single deterministic member (no shuffles,
\code{"none"} normalization). Note that with more than one member the feature
permutations are drawn with R's random number generator, so results are a
faithful reproduction of the reference ensemble but not bit-for-bit identical
to it; set the seed for reproducibility across runs.
}

\subsection{Device support}{

Computation runs on CPU by default and on CUDA when \code{device = "cuda"} and a
GPU is available. The Apple \code{"mps"} backend is \strong{not} supported: the bundled
libtorch MPS kernels crash on parts of the model, so requesting \code{"mps"} issues
a warning and falls back to CPU.
}

\subsection{Pretrained weights}{

The released TabICL checkpoints are distributed as a Python \code{.ckpt}. They must
first be converted to the two files brulee reads
(\verb{<task>.config.json} and \verb{<task>.model.safetensors}) and cached under
\verb{~/.cache/TabICL/<version>/<date>/<Classification|Regression>/}. \code{brulee_tab_icl()}
loads the cached checkpoint for the task automatically and errors if none is
found. Automatic download is not yet available; populate the cache offline with
the conversion tooling in \verb{dev/tabicl/}.
}
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
# Requires converted TabICL weights cached under ~/.cache/TabICL/ (see the
# "Pretrained weights" section and dev/tabicl/).

if (torch::torch_is_installed() & rlang::is_installed("modeldata")) {
  data(penguins, package = "modeldata")
  penguins <- na.omit(penguins)

  in_train <- sample(seq_len(nrow(penguins)), 250)
  tr <- penguins[in_train, ]
  te <- penguins[-in_train, ]

  # Classification (uses the cached classification checkpoint)
  cls_fit <- brulee_tab_icl(species ~ ., data = tr)
  predict(cls_fit, te)
  predict(cls_fit, te, type = "prob")

  # Regression (uses the cached regression checkpoint)
  reg_fit <- brulee_tab_icl(body_mass_g ~ ., data = tr)
  predict(reg_fit, te)
}
}
}
